Rub the @flank steak{2} with the @ras-el-hanout{1.5} spice and allow it to come to room temperature.

Add the @water{250%ml} to a #pot with the @vegetable stock pot{1} and bring to the boil. Peel and finely chop the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and finely chopped). Finely chop the @spring onion{2}(finely chopped, including the green parts). Peel the @carrot{2}(peeled and sliced into thin rounds) and slice into rounds as thinly as possible. Cut the @red pepper{1}(cut in half, stalk and seeds removed) in half, remove the stalk and seeds and slice thinly into strips.

Remove your #pot of stock from the heat and add the @couscous{150}. Cover and set aside.

Meanwhile, put a #frying pan on medium heat and add a splash of @olive oil{}. Once hot, cook your garlic, spring onion, carrot, and red pepper for ~{4-5%minutes} until softened slightly.

Season each steak on both sides with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Heat another #frying pan over medium-high heat and add a splash of @olive oil{}. When the pan is hot, add your steak and sear on each side for ~{2-3%minutes} until nicely coloured.

> Tip: This cooks your steak medium-rare. If you like your steak well-done, cook it for an additional 3 mins on each side.

Remove your steak from the #frying pan and set aside.

Whilst your steak is searing, roughly chop the @coriander{½%bunch}(roughly chopped) and add three-quarters of it to the pan with your vegetables. Remove from the heat, add the @baby spinach{to taste} and a splash of @olive oil{}. Fold everything together. When your couscous has fully soaked up all the water, add that to the pan as well and stir to combine.

Grate in the zest of the @lemon{½}(zested and juiced) and squeeze in some of its juice.

Slice each steak, on the diagonal, into 1cm strips and serve with your couscous and vegetable mix. Garnish with your remaining coriander.